Note
Increase from fiscal year (FY) 2026 to FY 2027 provides for further disruptive technology development and prototyping, additional systems engineering and integration
activities with partner space capabilities such as Space-based Interceptor (SBI), operational Hypersonic and Ballistic Tracking Space Sensor (HBTSS), and Proliferated
Warfighting Space Architecture (PWSA) for Missile Defense System-Next.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Space Applications for Missile Defense (SAMD) provides the functional elements of the Missile Defense Agency (MDA) Contractor Support Services, Federally Funded
Research and Development Center/University Affiliated Research Center, and civilian manpower into a single entity that provides acquisition, financial, and technical
support across the MDA Space Capabilities enterprise. In addition to the functional elements, this activity provides for developing and prototyping new space-based
capabilities to support missile defense. SAMD also provides the MDSEA platform, Missile Defense Space Center (MDSC) infrastructure and Test and Integration
Lab (TIL) which provides multi-mission ground segment and test integration support for current and future Missile Defense System Space Programs, to include the
Discriminating Space Sensor (DSS) program. MDSEA is a highly scalable compute platform that provides mission commanding, data processing, and data storage
services for the missile defense space architecture.

 The Spacebased Kill Assessment (SKA) system was composed of two segments: a space segment and a ground segment. The space segment was composed of a
 network of small infrared sensors (sensors, processor cards and cabling), each mated to a different satellite. The total number of sensors and their network placement
 was specifically tailored for the hit and kill assessment missions. The space segment included key design features to improve its resiliency. The ground segment
 monitored the health and status of the on-orbit sensors, commanded the sensors to perform the hit and kill assessment mission, and analyzed the data to make a hit/kill
 assessment determination. The ground segment also included the equipment necessary for communications security and information assurance. The Missile Defense
 Space Center (MDSC) provided the critical infrastructure for SKA data, routing SKA data between the commercial payload integrator and the multi-mission MDSEA. Due
 to higher Department of War priorities, the SKA experiment was cancelled in FY 2026 after successfully demonstrating hit-assessment capabilities from space.

